    <p><img src="/images/sunny_beach.svg" class="square_left" alt="sunny beach">
    To communicate verbally or in written form about the concept of “happiness”, writers must use a lot of words to communicate. Words like "positive", "sunny", "enthusiastic", and so many more. But words are subjective, meaning that each of them means something slightly different to all of us, and sequential, meaning that, when used in sentences, they're subject to structural rules. Words are great when precise, concrete meaning is possible, but less effective when multiple meanings are needed to be conveyed simultaneously or when a concept is vague or multi-faceted.
    </p>
    <p>Again, none of this is to say that drawing, collaging, model-making, et cetera, is more precise than words all the time, but that combining these options with words  makes your communications simultaneously more precise and more dense. Using both, your communications can convey more ideas in a shorter span of time than just using one method or the other can. Even if someone is not practiced at drawing or making models, the act of drawing or making itself allows people to follow the creative logic of the solution, while descriptive words elaborate on that logic. This is helpful for getting everyone on the same page as well as for starting to explore design ideas.</p>

    <h2>This is Just Show And Tell</h2>
    <p>In grade school, many students in the United States engage in a game called “Show and Tell”. In this exercise, students bring in an object they think is interesting, show it to the class, and then tell the class something about that object.
    </p>
    <p>One of the purposes of this exercise is to teach students about representational forms. For example, although a student cannot bring to class the hike in the woods they took over the weekend, they can bring the cool rock they picked up on that hike as a representation of what they did. By connecting the tangible rocks with the intangible hike, students are able to make generalizable connections about the elements of a hike, where to find rocks, and what future hikes or rocks might be like.
    </p>
    <p>As adults, images and objects function in the same way: the visualization allows for general communication about an experience, substance, process, etc. that cannot be present. For this reason, the old game of show and tell as useful in meetings as it was in your grade school’s class.
    </p>


